# UCSC Strikes: How to Eat

When the campus is on strike, where are you supposed to eat? During the recent American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees (AFSCME) strike, all but one dining hall was left open for the entire campus, which was the College 9/John R. Lewis dining hall. Known for its tall ceilings and wide food selection, this prestigious dining hall was unrecognizable during the strike, with every seat taken twice over.

![][image1]

[image1]: <data:image/jpeg;base64,>

[University of California, Santa Cruz Dining. Wellness and Community. UCSC Dining](https://dining.ucsc.edu/files/2025/06/Wellness-Community.jpg)  

[According to UCSC](https://news.ucsc.edu/2025/11/labor-strike-announced-for-nov-17-and-18/) AFSCME the strike lasted from Nov 17 till Nov 18 from which time the students lost access to buses, most dining services, and even the markets were so full they were often at capacity and were forced to close their doors. This degradation of student services was caused initially by the strike, however it is still up to the campus to ensure that all students are able to have food and eat. Many students say that while they understand the reasons behind the strike, the university didnt provide any rigid plan to help most students. Strikes are unavoidable, but their harm is, a proper plan by administrators could fully mitigate the disruption of a strike, and it seems this isnt happening.

![Union members with AFSCME Local 3299 at UC Santa Cruz and across the University of California system performed a two-day Unfair Labor Practice strike in November 2024. (Aric Sleeper - Santa Cruz Sentinel file)][image2]

[image2]: <data:image/jpeg;base64,>

[Photograph from Santa Cruz Sentinel. *Santa Cruz Sentinel*, 21 Nov. 2025](https://www.santacruzsentinel.com/2025/11/19/uc-santa-cruz-workers-join-labor-strike-for-higher-wages/)  

The strike took place in protest of the death of a bus worker which had made several complaints about the improper state of the buses, which later led to his death. Since his death in Dec, 2023 the campus has entered negotiations which concluded in an agreement after 17 months, yet the strike still took place due to the union's previous commitment. This strike included not only AFSCME but also the California Nurse Association (CNA), patient care technical workers (EX), and Local 3299 service workers (SX) so while this strike is in service of AFSCME everyone was involved in someway.  

Dining services were almost non-existent during the strike, so how should students plan their meals for future strikes? One popular option is ordering out, however, given the high prices this can add up quickly; another option is cooking meals during the strike, however most cooking equipment is outright banned in school dorms which limits you to ramen and other microwave-ready meals. Because of this, many students are forced to get food off-campus by means of walking or paying for an Uber. Planning for future strikes may mean building a small stock of non-perishable food that can last the duration of the strike, and remaining up-to-date with the latest dining hall news.  

Many students are frustrated at how the university handled the situation, with many students being forced to walk the entire hill just to get something to eat. Ironically, the people affected the most are the students paying the most, such as students on the 7-day Unlimited Meal Plan, which is basically useless when the dining halls are closed. Students in the dorms were hit especially hard, with almost no options for meals outside the university owned services. For many, this was a wake-up call that, due to the campus being so isolated, highlighted the dependence we have on these unprotected campus services.
